{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783437217887,"sessionID":"ses_0c2dd1dfcffeawJ3GCJmwMFkLa","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_lKIrXzTUI0qERxsqZ2XIGi0K","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"parent-hub-vocab-sync|buildModePrefixes|mode-registry|routerSignals|vocabulary","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills","include":"*.{cjs,js,mjs,ts,json,md}"},"output":"Found 100 matches (more matches available)\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-quality-control/README.md:\n  Line 80: The shared create-quality-control backbone lives at `../shared`. The single advisor identity and routing registry live at the hub root: `../graph-metadata.json`, `../description.json`, `../mode-registry.json`, and `../hub-router.json`.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/hub-router.json:\n  Line 15:   \"routerSignals\": {\n\n  Line 52:   \"vocabularyClasses\": {\n\n  Line 54:       \"keywords\": [\"deep-loop-workflows\", \"deep-loop\", \"deep loop\", \"mode-registry\", \"workflowmode\", \"runtimeloop-type\", \"backendkind\", \"convergence-detection\", \"externalized-state\", \"runtime-loop\", \"improvement-host\"]\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/SKILL.md:\n  Line 8: <!-- Keywords: deep-loop-workflows, deep-loop, deep-research, deep-review, deep-ai-council, deep-improvement, context-gathering, reuse-catalog, autoresearch, iterative-research, code-audit, severity-findings, P0-P1-P2, ai-council, council-deliberation, multi-seat-planning, agent-improvement, benchmark-harness, model-benchmark, skill-benchmark, non-dev-ai-system, convergence-detection, externalized-state, coverage-graph, mode-registry, workflowmode, runtimeloop-type, backendkind -->\n\n  Line 12: One skill, four active workflow families, one shared backend. `deep-loop-workflows` is the public, advisor-routable home for active deep-loop personas; `deep-loop-runtime` is the frozen, MCP-free backend it consumes. This hub holds NO per-mode convergence, state, or synthesis logic — each active mode keeps its own contract in its packet, and the hub only routes by `workflowMode` through `mode-registry.json`.\n\n  Line 37: Routing is **registry-driven** (invokable-hub, Option E). `mode-registry.json` is the single source of truth; the hub reads it and does not re-derive the mapping. When invoked as `Skill(deep-loop-workflows[, \"<mode>: <request>\"])`, the hub classifies the request to a `workflowMode`, resolves it through the registry, and loads `registry[mode].packet`. The advisor routes any deep-loop query to the single identity `deep-loop-workflows`; the hub then picks the mode. The `/deep:*` commands and native agent types remain as complementary surfaces — they reach the same packets through static routers/agent definitions — and the hub holds NO per-mode logic.\n\n  Line 49: guard mode-registry.json inside SKILL_ROOT and read it as data\n\n  Line 64: Intent classification favors the single dominant active deep-loop mode; a mode hint (`research: ...`, `review: ...`, `ai-council: ...`, or an improvement lane) overrides the classifier. The legacy advisor projection maps stay hardcoded and drift-guarded against the registry, and the command files remain static routers with hardcoded asset/mode routing; neither resolves from `mode-registry.json` at runtime, but both stay equal to its projection.\n\n  Line 76:   mode-registry.json     # the three-tier discriminator + advisorRouting (single source of truth)\n\n  Line 82: Each active mode packet keeps its own `SKILL.md`, `references/`, `scripts/`, `assets/`, `feature_catalog/`, or `manual_testing_playbook/` as applicable, with internal paths repointed and **no per-packet `graph-metadata.json`** — only this hub carries one, so the advisor discovers exactly one skill. The `deep-ai-council` packet folder follows the standard `folder == packetSkillName` convention (`deep-ai-council`); its legacy public surfaces (the `/deep:ai-council` command and the `ai-council` agent) intentionally keep the shorter `ai-council` key, so always resolve the packet path through `mode-registry.json` rather than hardcoding it.\n\n  Line 92: - **ALWAYS** resolve a mode through `mode-registry.json` (read the `packet` key; never hardcode a router mapping or packet path in the hub).\n\n  Line 93: - **ALWAYS** keep advisor projection maps hardcoded and drift-guarded against the registry; command mode routing is still hardcoded in the command files and does not resolve through `mode-registry.json`.\n\n  Line 105: - A new mode is needed beyond the seven registered — extend `mode-registry.json` and open a packet, do not bolt logic onto the hub.\n\n  Line 115: - Registry: `mode-registry.json` (the routing contract — the authoritative `packet` paths).\n\n  Line 121: - The hub resolves one primary active `workflowMode` for the request through `mode-registry.json` (improvement folds to the right lane via the registry, never by array order).\n\n  Line 146: - Sibling example: `.opencode/skills/sk-design/` (the same invokable-hub + `mode-registry.json` Option E pattern).\n\n  Line 147: - Registry: `mode-registry.json` (this hub's routing contract).\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/z_archive/cli-codex-retired/SKILL.retired.md:\n  Line 364: 12. **Design Standards Loading (surface-aware contract)** — When dispatching for design or UI work, instruct the dispatched session to: (1) load `sk-design` (the hub); (2) let the hub resolve a `workflowMode` through `mode-registry.json` (interface / foundations / motion / audit / md-generator); (3) load the selected mode packet, set the design register, and run that mode's design verification; (4) if the work feeds Open Design, carry the `mcp-open-design` pairing — the transport never decides taste. Fallback: if the design mode cannot be determined confidently, ask for the surface and design intent. NEVER treat `mcp-figma` or `mcp-open-design` as the taste authority, or hardcode obsolete flat design skills in dispatch prompts.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/SKILL.md:\n  Line 431: - ✅ Council requests route to the `deep-ai-council` advisor/packet surface (`packetSkillName` and `legacyAdvisorId` in `mode-registry.json`); `deep-ai-council` is the packet folder/SKILL.md name (folder == name), while the dispatched agent identity remains `ai-council`.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-opencode/SKILL.md:\n  Line 348: 13. **Design Standards Loading (surface-aware contract)** — When dispatching for design or UI work, instruct the dispatched session to: (1) load `sk-design` (the hub); (2) let the hub resolve a `workflowMode` through `mode-registry.json` (interface / foundations / motion / audit / md-generator / design-mcp-open-design); (3) load the selected mode packet, set the design register, and run that mode's design verification; (4) if the work feeds Open Design, carry the `design-mcp-open-design` pairing (a nested transport packet of the hub) — the transport never decides taste. Fallback: if the design mode cannot be determined confidently, ask for the surface and design intent. NEVER treat `mcp-figma` or `design-mcp-open-design` as the taste authority, or hardcode obsolete flat design skills in dispatch prompts.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-benchmark/README.md:\n  Line 84: The single advisor identity, `mode-registry.json`, `hub-router.json`, `description.json`, and `graph-metadata.json` live at the `sk-doc` hub root.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/.goal-state/.archive/7365735f30653737666337393466666542676f41496c6230346630384f66.json:\n  Line 4:   \"objective\": \"Autonomously plan, implement, test, and verify all 5 phases of the deep-agent-router-and-orchestration tree, in dependency order, until each passes its acceptance gate. SPEC TREE: .opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/001-deep-agent-router-and-orchestration/ (phase parent; research DONE). EVIDENCE BASE: research/research.md (v2) + research/iterations/iteration-00{1-6}.md. BUILD ON IT — do not re-derive. Concrete deep.md draft = iteration-004.md; 4-mode pre-route edit map = research.md §3; FIX-5 false-negative = §5. INTEGRITY CAVEAT: cited prior research (030/010, ../001) is MISSING from disk; treat mis-route taxonomy (modes A/B/C) + FIX-ranking as operator-asserted axioms. Phase 001 T004 resolves this (recover OR formally accept-as-axiom via decision-record). EXECUTE IN ORDER — each phase: /speckit:plan → implement (sk-code skill) → test → verify, before the next: 1. 001-route-proof-validation (L2): R1 add route-proof fields (mode/target_agent/agent_definition_loaded/echoed Resolved route) to iteration+delta records in all 4 deep_*_auto.yaml validators; R10 prior-research resolution; C1-C3 citation fixes. GATE: a schema-valid-but-wrong-mode artifact is REJECTED (closes F27); validate.sh --strict passes. 2. 002-agent-dispatch-hardening (L2): R2 land .opencode/agents/deep.md from iteration-004 draft (mode:primary, registry-aligned route table, 5 mis-route guards); R3 .claude/agents/deep.md mirror; R5 Deep Route field in orchestrate.md:206-208 + .claude mirror. GATE: deep.md resolves correct sub-agent per mode via mode-registry.json; Claude-flex test (iter-6 table) all PASS; validate.sh --strict. 3. 003-command-pre-route-headers (L2): R4 Resolved route headers across all 4 modes — research/review (template+CLI), context (inline seat+one-shot, no standalone template), council (round prompt + executor_config_json; no YAML if_cli_opencode branch). Exact file:line in research.md §3. GATE: each mode's prompt begins with the header...\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/tests/integration/review-depth-graph.vitest.ts:\n  Line 63: describe('review-depth graph vocabulary fixtures', () => {\n\n  Line 64:   it('upserting BUG_CLASS node succeeds because the Phase G graph vocabulary contract is live', async () => {\n\n  Line 96:   it('upserts candidate vocabulary edges with review graph relation allow-list coverage', async () => {\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/changelog/v2.2.0.0.md:\n  Line 7: This release aligns `deep-ai-council` with the shared deep-skill resource model while preserving its planning-only domain. It adds a council-specific quick reference, loop protocol, and runtime asset family so operators see the same resource shape as `deep-research` and `deep-review` without copy-pasting their loop vocabulary.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-changelog/SKILL.md:\n  Line 274: The shared template does not define `Added`, `Changed`, `Fixed`, or `Removed` as canonical section names. If a caller asks for those headings, translate the content into the template's plain category vocabulary unless the user explicitly requires a different external format.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-changelog/references/worked_examples.md:\n  Line 66: - `#### Documentation` and `#### Commands` use the shared category vocabulary.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-prompt/references/patterns_evaluation.md:\n  Line 652: | 10-12 | Clear, specific, minimal ambiguity, well-chosen vocabulary |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-prompt/references/depth_framework.md:\n  Line 306: | 10-12 | Clear, specific, minimal ambiguity, well-chosen vocabulary |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/scripts/check-contract-drift.cjs:\n  Line 40:   '.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/mode-registry.json',\n\n  Line 143:   if (/\\/mode-registry\\.json$/.test(sourcePath)) return true;\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md:\n  Line 222: Detection-layer OpenCode plugin with two checks: flags/blocks a Task dispatch whose declared Deep Route mode disagrees with `mode-registry.json`'s entry for the resolved target agent, and flags/blocks a session-scoped loop-like repeated `orchestrate`-to-command-owned-loop-executor dispatch. Also sweeps/archives/prunes its own `.loop-guard-state` directory on `session.created` so it does not grow unbounded.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/scripts/compile-command-contracts.cjs:\n  Line 15:   modeRegistry: '.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/mode-registry.json',\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-research/behavior_benchmark/scenarios/RSB-006-auto-missing-inputs.md:\n  Line 33: A pass is a fast failure that names the missing inputs — the marker vocabulary must read as a missing/required/cannot/unresolved statement — and terminates with no dispatch.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-research/behavior_benchmark/scenarios/RSB-001-auto-run-specified.md:\n  Line 35: A pass runs autonomously to its declared iteration cap: at least one task event is dispatched to the `deep-research` leaf agent, the research/dispatch vocabulary surfaces in the visible output, and the run terminates inside budget without a watchdog kill.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-research/behavior_benchmark/scenarios/RSB-003-vague-natural-ask.md:\n  Line 33: A pass is a targeted clarifying question that names what is missing — the research subject — and halts. The marker vocabulary must read as a clarification request, not a research answer.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/manual_testing_playbook/03--validation/mk-deep-loop-guard.md:\n  Line 15: Detection-layer OpenCode plugin (`tool.execute.before` hook) with two independent checks: (1) flags/blocks a Task dispatch whose declared Deep Route mode disagrees with `mode-registry.json`'s entry for the resolved target agent; (2) flags/blocks a session-scoped loop-like repeated hand-off from `orchestrate` to a command-owned loop executor (`deep-research`, `deep-review`, `deep-improvement`, `prompt-improver`) that lacks a command-driven iteration marker. Both checks share `resolveTargetIdentity()`, which parses the real target agent from `Deep Route: ... target_agent=@X` / `Agent: @X` prompt text, since real `orchestrate`-issued dispatches always set `subagent_type: \"general\"`.\n\n  Line 46: 4. Live fail-open check: temporarily move `mode-registry.json` aside, repeat step 3; confirm the dispatch completes normally (not blocked) despite reject mode being on.\n\n  Line 60: - A missing/corrupt `mode-registry.json`, or an unwritable `.opencode/skills/.loop-guard-state/` directory, starts blocking unrelated dispatches instead of failing open.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-research/SKILL.md:\n  Line 451: Cross-skill alignment: `deep-research` owns iterative investigation. Its shared resource family mirrors `deep-review` and `deep-ai-council`, but its vocabulary remains novelty, sources, negative knowledge,